The White House has issued a presidential proclamation declaring September as National Preparedness Month. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of preparedness in ensuring a resilient and secure nation. It encourages individuals, families, communities, and the private and nonprofit sectors to take responsibility for preparing for emergencies. The Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) is mentioned as a resource that supports and promotes citizen education and grassroots preparedness efforts. The proclamation calls upon all Americans to take steps to protect themselves, their families, and their neighbors by creating emergency supply kits, family emergency plans, and educating themselves about potential disasters. It also encourages coordination of emergency preparedness efforts within communities. The proclamation concludes by urging the people of the United States to observe National Preparedness Month with appropriate activities, events, and training to enhance national resilience.